'''Forced Abortion Condemnation Act''' is a [[Bill (proposed law)|bill]], introduced at the [[105th United States Congress]] on September 29, 1997 by the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Sponsor (legislative)|sponsor]] [[Tillie Fowler]].<ref name="Govtrack">{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/105/hr2570|title=H.R. 2570 (105th): Forced Abortion Condemnation Act|publisher =[[GovTrack]]|accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref> It sought to "condemn those officials of the [[Chinese Communist Party]], the [[Government of the People's Republic of China]], and other persons who are involved in the enforcement of [[forced abortion]]s by preventing such persons from entering or remaining in the United States".<ref name="Govtrack"/> On November 6, 1997 the bill passed the [[U.S. House of Representatives]], but was not passed by the [[United States Senate|Senate]].<ref name="Govtrack"/>
The bill was re-introduced on January 6, 1999 at the subsequent meeting of the U.S. Congress,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/106/hr138|title=H.R. 138 (106th): Forced Abortion Condemnation Act|publisher =[[GovTrack]]|accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref> but was not enacted either as it was opposed by the [[Clinton administration]].
