{{Other uses|Grey Nuns Hospital (disambiguation){{!}}Grey Nuns Hospital}} {{Coord|45.500322|-73.554845|format=dms|display=title}} {{Infobox building | name = Grey Nuns' Hospital | native_name = Ancien hôpital général de Montréal (Hôpital-des-Sœurs-Grises) | native_name_lang = fr | alternate_names = Hôpital général des frères Charon, Former General Hospital of Montreal | image = Hopgeneral.JPG | caption = Grey Nuns' Hospital in 2009 | map_type = Canada Montreal | coordinates = {{coord|45.5|-73.5548|display=inline}} | map_caption = Location in Montreal | building_type = Former hospital | architectural_style = Early [[French Canadian]] architecture | owner = | current_tenants = | address = 138 Saint-Pierre Street | location_town = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]] | location_country = [[Canada]] | completion_date = 1765 | embedded = {{Designation list |embed=yes |designation1=NHSC |designation1_offname=Grey Nuns' Hospital National Historic Site of Canada |designation1_date=1973 | designation2 = Quebec | designation2_offname =Ancien hôpital général de Montréal | designation2_type =Classified heritage immovable | designation2_criteria = | designation2_date =2013 }} | references = }}
The '''Grey Nuns' Hospital''' (also known as '''Hôpital général des frères Charron''') was a [[hospital]] in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada that operated from 1695 to 1880. It is located south of [[Place d'Youville]] and west of [[Rue Saint-Pierre]].
== History == [[File:Maison Mere dYouville.jpg|thumb|left|The building in 2008]] The name ''Hôpital général des frères Charron'' ({{lang-en|General Hospital of the Frères Charron}}) refers to a [[New France|French]] religious community of the same name. It focused on care of the poor. The hospital was built outside the [[Fortifications of Montreal]] in 1695. Management and hospital administration were entrusted to the [[Grey Nuns]] in 1747.
The hospital suffered a major fire in 1765 and was rebuilt again according to the style of French architecture, that is to say, with large walls composed of rough stone called [[rubble]] that had been squared and covered in plaster. The architecture, which is very utilitarian, is rudimentary and has little ornamentation. The gable roof prevents the accumulation of snow in winter. The structure, being less massive and simpler to build meant a lower risk of fire. Finally, esses are used to reinforce the structure with stems screwed into the wood frame.
In 1880, the nuns decided to rent the building in order to maintain administrative offices in their communities.
In 1971, the Grey Nuns decided to return to their first mother-house. Major renovations of the building were undertaken.
The site was designated a [[National Historic Sites of Canada|National Historic Site of Canada]] in 1973.<ref>{{CRHP|9651|Grey Nuns' Hospital National Historic Site of Canada|29 September 2012}}</ref>
