{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = {{PAGENAME}} | synonyms = | image = | width = | alt = | caption = | pronounce = | field = [[Gynecology]] | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = differential: [[atrophic vaginitis]], malignancies | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} '''Postcoital bleeding''' is [[bleeding]] from the vagina in women after [[sexual intercourse]] and may or may not be associated with pain.<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Boukhanni|first=Lahssen|last2=Dhibou|first2=Hanane|last3=Zilfi|first3=Wafaa|last4=Housseini|first4=Kawtar Iraki|last5=Benkeddour|first5=Yasser Ait|last6=Aboulfalah|first6=Abderrahim|last7=Asmouki|first7=Hamid|last8=Soummani|first8=Abderraouf|date=2016-03-25|title=Les hémorragies post coïtales: à propos de 68 cas et revue de literature|journal=The Pan African Medical Journal|volume=23|doi=10.11604/pamj.2016.23.131.9073|pmc=4885701|pmid=27279958}}</ref> The bleeding can be from the uterus, cervix, vagina and other tissue or organs located near the vagina.<ref name=":2" /> Poistcoital bleeding can be one of the first indications of cervical cancer.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shapley|first=Mark|last2=Jordan|first2=Joanne|last3=Croft|first3=Peter R|date=2006-06-01|title=A systematic review of postcoital bleeding and risk of cervical cancer|journal=The British Journal of General Practice|volume=56|issue=527|pages=453–460|pmc=1839021|pmid=16762128}}</ref><ref name=":0" /> There are other reasons why a woman may bleed after intercourse. Some women will bleed after intercourse for the first time but others will not. The hymen may bleed if it is stretched since it is thin tissue. Other activities may have an effect on the vagina such as sports and tampon use.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhs.uk/chq/Pages/2372.aspx?CategoryID=118&SubCategoryID=121|title=Does a woman always bleed when she has sex for the first time? - Health questions - NHS Choices|last=Choices|first=N. H. S.|date=2016-07-12|access-date=2018-02-04}}</ref> Postcoital bleeding may stop without treatment.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shapley|first=M|last2=Blagojevic-Bucknall|first2=M|last3=Jordan|first3=Kp|last4=Croft|first4=Pr|date=2013-10-01|title=The epidemiology of self-reported intermenstrual and postcoital bleeding in the perimenopausal years|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/1471-0528.12218/abstract|journal=BJOG: An International Journal of Obstetrics & Gynaecology|language=en|volume=120|issue=11|pages=1348–1355|doi=10.1111/1471-0528.12218|issn=1471-0528}}</ref> In some instances, postcoital bleeding may resemble menstrual irregularities.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/14651858.CD007595.pub3/abstract|title=Repeated use of pre- and postcoital hormonal contraception for prevention of pregnancy|last=Halpern|first=Vera|last2=Raymond|first2=Elizabeth G|last3=Lopez|first3=Laureen M|date=2014|publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Ltd|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en|doi=10.1002/14651858.cd007595.pub3}}</ref> Postcoital bleeding may occur throughout pregnancy. The presence of cervical polyps may result in postcoital bleeding during pregnancy because the tissue of the polyps is more easily damaged.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/841914663|title=Guidelines for nurse practitioners in ambulatory obstetric settings|last=J.|first=Cibulka, Nancy|date=2013|publisher=Springer Publishing Company|others=Barron, Mary Lee.|year=|isbn=9780826195579|location=New York|pages=240|oclc=841914663}}</ref> Postcoital bleeding can be due to trauma after consensual and non-consensual sexual intercourse.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boukhanni|first=Lahssen|last2=Dhibou|first2=Hanane|last3=Zilfi|first3=Wafaa|last4=Housseini|first4=Kawtar Iraki|last5=Benkeddour|first5=Yasser Ait|last6=Aboulfalah|first6=Abderrahim|last7=Asmouki|first7=Hamid|last8=Soummani|first8=Abderraouf|date=2016|title=Les hémorragies post coïtales: à propos de 68 cas et revue de littérature|url=http://www.panafrican-med-journal.com/content/article/23/131/full/|journal=Pan African Medical Journal|language=fr|volume=23|pages=|doi=10.11604/pamj.2016.23.131.9073|via=}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9GclDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA120&dq=Postcoital+bleeding&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjThKyvppTZAhUKmVkKHUK2CmEQ6AEINTAC#v=onepage&q=Postcoital%20bleeding&f=false|title=Netter's Obstetrics and Gynecology E-Book|last=Smith|first=Roger P.|date=2017-02-16|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=9780323523509|language=en}}</ref>
A diagnosis to determine the cause will include obtaining a medical history and assessing the symptoms. Treatment is not always necessary.<ref name="nhs">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhs.uk/chq/Pages/977.aspx?CategoryID=118|title=What causes a woman to bleed after sex? - Health questions - NHS Choices|last=Choices|first=N. H. S.|date=2018|website=|access-date=2018-02-04}}</ref>
== Causes == Vaginal bleeding after sex is a symptom that can indicate: * [[pelvic inflammatory disease]]<ref name="nhs" /> * uterine disease<ref name="mscape" /> * [[chlamydia]] or other [[sexually transmitted infection]]<ref name="nhs" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W-5kAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA423&lpg=PA423&dq=Postcoital+bleeding+men+anal&source=bl&ots=dNVlutnX3P&sig=WFi4e1vNMJTlezYWc1Cf7CNfYvU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiVt7qfpJTZAhWK2VMKHUbGAmc4ChDoAQhJMAk#v=onepage&q=Postcoital%20bleeding%20men%20anal&f=false|title=Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine E-Book|last=Walker|first=Brian R.|last2=Colledge|first2=Nicki R.|date=2013-12-06|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=9780702051036|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h65BJiYvt_oC&pg=PA441&lpg=PA441&dq=Postcoital+bleeding+men+anal&source=bl&ots=HvDptyHCr4&sig=KHznydYEdmTTL9QWvzZRzyos44A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiVt7qfpJTZAhWK2VMKHUbGAmc4ChDoAQhNMAo#v=onepage&q=Postcoital%20bleeding&f=false|title=Hutchison's Clinical Methods,An Integrated Approach to Clinical Practice With STUDENT CONSULT Online Access,23: Hutchison's Clinical Methods|last=Drake|first=William M.|last2=Hutchison|first2=Robert|date=2012-01-01|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=0702040916|language=en}}</ref> * [[atrophic vaginitis]]<ref name="nhs" /> * [[childbirth]] *inadequate [[vaginal lubrication]]<ref name=":2" /> * benign [[Polyp (medicine)|polyps]] * [[Cervical ectropion|cervical erosion]] (inflammation of the cervix)<ref name="nhs" /><ref name=":2" /> * cervical or [[vaginal cancer]]<ref name="nhs" /> * anatomical abnormality of the [[uterine malformation|uterus]], [[vaginal anomalies|vagina]] or both.<ref name = mscape>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/412468|title=Postcoital Bleeding in a Premenopausal Patient|last=|first=|date=|website=www.medscape.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020415190326/http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/412468|archive-date=2002-04-15|dead-url=yes|access-date=2018-02-04}}</ref> * [[pregnancy]] * [[Endometrial polyp|endometrial polyps]] * [[endometrial hyperplasia]] * [[Endometrial cancer|endometrial carcinoma]] * [[Leiomyoma|leiomyomata]] * [[cervicitis]] * [[Cervical intraepithelial neoplasia|cervical dysplasia]] * [[endometriosis]] * coagulation defects * [[Injury|trauma]]<ref name=":2" /> * Bleeding from hemorrhoids and vulvar lesions can be mistaken for postcoital bleeding.<ref name=":2" /> Post coital bleeding can occur with discharge, itching, or irritation. This may be due to ''[[Trichomonas]]'' or ''[[Candidiasis|Candida]]''.<ref name = mscape/> A lack of estrogen can make vaginal tissue thinner and more susceptible to bleeding. Some have proposed that [[birth control pills]] may cause postcoital bleeding.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dh.gov.uk/en/Publicationsandstatistics/Publications/PublicationsPolicyAndGuidance/DH_113478|title=Clinical practice guidelines for the assessment of young women aged 20-24 with abnormal vaginal bleeding|last=Health|first=Department of|date=2010-03-03|access-date=2018-02-04|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20101110212848/http://www.dh.gov.uk/en/Publicationsandstatistics/Publications/PublicationsPolicyAndGuidance/DH_113478|archivedate=2010-11-10|df=}}</ref>
Risk factors for developing postcoital bleeding are: low estrogen levels, rape and 'rough sex'.<ref name=":2" />
== Diagnosis and treatment == Tests and detailed examination are used to determine the cause of the bleeding: * a [[pregnancy test]] * a [[pelvic examination]]<ref name="nhs" /> * obtaining tissue samples * pap smear * [[Colposcopy|colposcopic]] examination of the vagina and cervix * [[ultrasound]] * histogram * cultures for bacteria<ref name="mscape" /> * biopsy of tissues<ref name=":2" />
A [[Referral (medicine)|referral]] may be made to a specialist.<ref name="nhs" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rcog.org.uk/en/guidelines-research-services/guidelines/postcoital-bleeding-query-bank/|title=Postcoital bleeding|last=|first=|date=|website=Royal College of Obstetricians &amp; Gynaecologists|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-05}}</ref> Imaging may not be necessary. Cryotherapy has been used but is not recommended.<ref name=":2" />
== Epidemiology == Postcoital bleeding rarely is associated with gynecological cancer in young women and its incidence is projected to drop due to the widespread [[Immunization|immunizations]] against [[Human papillomavirus infection|HPV]]. Postcoital bleeding has been most studied in women in the US. In a large Taiwanese study, the overall incidence of postcoital bleeding was found to be 39-59 per 100,000 women. Those with postcoital bleeding had a higher risk of [[Cervical intraepithelial neoplasia|cervical dysplasia]] and [[Cervical cancer|cervical cancer.]] [[Benignity|Benign]] causes of postcoital bleeding were associated with [[Cervical ectropion|cervical erosion]], ectropion, [[vaginitis]] and vulvovaginitis. Other associations were noted such as the presence of [[leukoplakia]] of the cervix, an [[Intrauterine device|intrauterine contraceptive device]], [[Cervical polyp|cervical polyps]], [[cervicitis]], [[menopause]], [[dyspareunia]], and [[vulvodynia]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Liu|first=Hsin-Li|last2=Chen|first2=Chuan-Mei|last3=Pai|first3=Lee-Wen|last4=Hwu|first4=Yueh-Juen|last5=Lee|first5=Horng-Mo|last6=Chung|first6=Yueh-Chin|date=2017-04-01|title=Comorbidity profiles among women with postcoital bleeding: a nationwide health insurance database|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00404-017-4327-7|journal=Archives of Gynecology and Obstetrics|language=en|volume=295|issue=4|pages=935–941|doi=10.1007/s00404-017-4327-7|issn=0932-0067}}</ref> In Scotland approximately 1 in 600 women aged 20-24 experience unexplained bleeding.<ref name=":0" /> A study of African women found an that trauma from consensual sexual intercourse was a cause of postcoital bleeding in young women.<ref name=":1" />
== In society and culture == In Islamic culture, postcoital bleeding may be desired to "satisfy cultural and/or religious 'needs'". It is controversial: {{Quote box|width=60em|align=left| quote = "From a Western-ethics perspective, the life-saving potential of the procedure is weighed against the role of the surgeon in directly assisting in a deception and in indirectly promoting cultural practices of sexual inequality. From an Islamic bioethical vantage point, jurists offer two opinions. The first is that the surgery is always impermissible. The second is that although the surgery is generally impermissible, it can become licit when the risks of not having postcoital bleeding harm are sufficiently great."<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bawany|first=Mohammad H.|last2=Padela|first2=Aasim I.|title=Hymenoplasty and Muslim Patients: Islamic Ethico-Legal Perspectives|url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1743609517312924|journal=The Journal of Sexual Medicine|volume=14|issue=8|pages=1003–1010|doi=10.1016/j.jsxm.2017.06.005}}</ref>}}
